<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="139" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,323]" pageId="10" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,153,179]" pageId="10" pageNumber="139">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riccardi" authorityYear="2020" box="[581,663,153,178]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Chaethippus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="notatus">
<emphasis box="[581,663,153,178]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="139">notatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” is a Latin adjective, meaning marked, referring to the brown stripes on the notum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="139" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,323]" pageId="10" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,225,251]" pageId="10" pageNumber="139">Remarks.</emphasis>
All species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1930" box="[481,623,224,250]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Chaethippus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[481,623,224,250]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="139">Chaethippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have several microtrichiae on the inner margin of the femoral organ (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 7–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1929]" captionTargetBox="[226,1353,194,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[214,1373,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–14. Chaethippus carioca sp.nov. paratypes. 7, habitus (scale bar 1 mm). 8, head in dorsal view. 9, head and thorax in profile (arrow indicates the fore coxa strong setae). 10, detail of the head in dorsal view. 11, tibial organ. 12, femoral organ. 13–14, male terminalia in terminal view (scale bar 0.1 mm). Abbreviations: bas, basiphallus; cer, cercus; dis, distiphallus; ep, epandrium; fr, frons; oc tr, ocellar triangle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904960/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="139">fig. 12</figureCitation>
). However, 
